  • Possess/Illegally Obtained Prescription, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 450.11(7)(h).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Called at 1:25 PM. Jacqueline Ipsa appears in person and with counsel Mary Burns. State appears by Charles Simono. State - have resolution - amend count #1 to 450.11(7)(h) - illegal possession of a prescrition drug without a valid prescription - reads maximum penalties - plead g/nc - joint recommendation of $300.00 fine plus costs and surcharges. Burns and Ipsa agree. Court amends count #1 to possession of prescription drug without a valid prescription contrary to 450.11(7)(h) - reads new charge and penalty. Ipsa pleads NC. Court has plea questionnaire, goes thru it, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived her constitutional rights by entering her plea and right to JT, accepts plea, adjudges guilty, proceed to sentencing. State - follow joint recommendation. Burns - follow joint recommendation. Ipsa withholds comment. Court sentences the defendant to the following: fine of $300 plus costs and surcharges totalling either $831.00 or $1114.50 (with $200.00 DNA surcharge) - paid at rate of $40.00/month commencing 8/15/14/CO, right to appeal, adjourned.
